  <data name="Help_Intro" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>MultiPingMonitor is a network utility that allows you to quickly monitor the availability of multiple hosts. Host monitors are easily added and removed, and dynamically resize with the application window. Color-coding allows you to tell at a glance the status of each host.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_BasicUsage_Header" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Basic Usage</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_BasicUsage_AppOverview_Sub" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Application overview</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_BasicUsage_MonitorHost_Sub" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Monitor a host</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_BasicUsage_MonitorHost_Text" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Enter a hostname or IP address into the textbox, then press Enter or click Ping. MultiPingMonitor will continuously ping the host until you click Stop. Responses are displayed in the output area above the textbox. The output section will turn green when the host is responding and red when it is not responding. If an error occurs, the output area will turn orange.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_BasicUsage_AddHost_Sub" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Add a host monitor</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_BasicUsage_AddHost_Prefix" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Click</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_BasicUsage_AddHost_Button" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Add Host</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_BasicUsage_AddHost_Suffix" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>from the menu bar, or use the keyboard shortcut,</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_BasicUsage_RemoveHost_Sub" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Remove a host monitor</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_BasicUsage_RemoveHost_Text" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>When you hover your mouse over a host monitor, an X icon will appear in the top-right corner. Click the X icon to remove that instance.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_BasicUsage_Columns_Sub" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Columns</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_BasicUsage_Columns_Text" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Click Columns in the menu bar then move the slider to the desired number of columns. This sets the number of host monitors to display in a single row. Additional rows will be created as needed.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_ExtraFeatures_Header" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Extra Features</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_PortMonitor_Sub" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Port Monitor</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_PortMonitor_Text_Before" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>To monitor a specific TCP port, simply enter the hostname or IP address followed by a colon and the desired port number. MultiPingMonitor will then continuously try to connect to the given port and display whether or not the connection is successful. Example -</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_PortMonitor_Text_After" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>, will monitor port 80 on SERVER01.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_TraceRoute_Sub" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Trace Route</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_TraceRoute_Text" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The trace route utility is used to measure network delays and determine the path taken to the given destination host. The utility can be accessed from the dropdown icon in the top right or by pressing Ctrl-T.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_FloodHost_Sub" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Flood Host</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_FloodHost_Text" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The flood host utility is used to generate a significant amount of ICMP packets. To limit the flow, the utility waits until a reply is received before sending the next ICMP packet. The utility can be accessed from dropdown icon in the top right or by pressing Ctrl-F.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_Options_Header" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Options</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_Options_PingInterval_Sub" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Ping interval</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_Options_PingInterval_Text" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The time to wait between sending each packet. The time can be specified in seconds, minutes, or hours.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_Options_PingTimeout_Sub" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Ping timeout</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_Options_PingTimeout_Text" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The maximum time to wait for a response, in seconds.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_Options_Email_Sub" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Send email when host goes down or up</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_Options_Email_Text" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Send an email each time a host changes status (from down to up or from up to down). A mail server, recipient email address, and from email address must all be specified.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_Options_AlwaysOnTop_Sub" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Keep window always on top</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_Options_AlwaysOnTop_Text" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>The MultiPingMonitor window will remain on top of all other application windows.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_Options_Logging_Sub" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Log all output to files</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_Options_Logging_Text" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Write all ping responses to a text file. The file will be named &lt;hostname&gt;.txt and will be saved to the specified directory. If the file already exists, new output will be appended to the existing file.</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_CommandLine_Header" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Command Line Usage</value>
  </data>
  <data name="Help_CommandLine_Usage" xml:space="preserve">
    <value>Usage: MultiPingMonitor [-i interval] [-w timeout] [&lt;target_host&gt;...]</value>
  </data>
